Table: Automatic Data Mapping
What makes this Table special?
In ezui, the Table is “Smart.” You don’t have to tell it what the headers are or manually type every row. Instead, you give it a List of Objects, and the Table handles the rest.
Step 1: The ITable Contract
To show your data in a table, your class (like Student or Book) must “implement” the ITable interface. This tells the table how to “read” your object.
public class Student implements ITable {
    private String id, name, grade;

    // The Table calls this to build the top header row
    public String[] getHeaders() { 
        return new String[]{"ID", "Student Name", "Current Grade"}; 
    }

    // The Table calls this to fill in each row
    public String[] getValues() { 
        return new String[]{id, name, grade}; 
    }
}

Creating a HashSet
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

Set&lt;String&gt; enrolled = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();







Note


We declare the variable as Set&lt;String&gt; (the interface) and create a HashSet&lt;String&gt; (the implementation). This is the standard Java style.

Iterating Over a Set
Since Sets have no index, you use a for-each loop:
Set&lt;String&gt; fruits = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
fruits.add("Mango");
fruits.add("Apple");
fruits.add("Banana");

for (String fruit : fruits) {
    System.out.println(fruit);
}







Warning


The order of iteration is not guaranteed with HashSet. You might see Apple, Banana, Mango or any other order. If order matters, use TreeSet (alphabetical) or LinkedHashSet (insertion order).

Set Use Cases

Checking for duplicates: Add items one by one; if size() stays the same, you had a duplicate.
Membership testing: Is this username taken? Is this word in the dictionary?
Removing duplicates from a list: Dump an ArrayList into a HashSet and all duplicates vanish.


// Remove duplicates from a list
ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(List.of(3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5));
Set&lt;Integer&gt; unique = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(nums);
System.out.println(unique);  // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 9] — no duplicates

Creating a HashMap
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map&lt;String, String&gt; phoneBook = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
The first type is the key type, the second is the value type.

Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; scores  = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();  // name → score
Map&lt;Integer, String&gt; idToName = new HashMap&lt;&gt;(); // ID → name
Map&lt;String, Double&gt;  prices   = new HashMap&lt;&gt;(); // item → price

Iterating Over a Map
Loop over entries (key + value pairs) using entrySet():
Map&lt;String, Integer&gt; scores = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
scores.put("Alice", 95);
scores.put("Bob",   82);
scores.put("Carol", 88);

for (Map.Entry&lt;String, Integer&gt; entry : scores.entrySet()) {
