Code Anatomy - Handling Multiple Errors
try {
    String input = scanner.nextLine();
    int num = Integer.parseInt(input); // Potential NumberFormatException
    System.out.println(10 / num);      // Potential ArithmeticException
} catch (NumberFormatException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: Please enter a valid integer.");
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: Cannot divide by zero.");
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Something else went wrong: " + e.getMessage());
} finally {
    System.out.println("Cleanup code can go here.");
}

Pro-Tip: Always catch specific exceptions first. If you catch the general Exception class first, the more specific ones below it will never be reached.

Defining and Throwing Your Own Exceptions

You don’t have to wait for the JVM to find an error. You can trigger one yourself to enforce rules.
The throw Keyword:

public void setAge(int age) {
    if (age &lt; 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Age cannot be negative!");
    }
    this.age = age;
}

This is “Defensive Programming”—stopping bad data before it ruins your program’s state.

Exam Prep - “What is the Output?”
Question: What prints if the user enters “0”?
try {
    int x = 5 / Integer.parseInt(input);
    System.out.println("A");
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("B");
} finally {
    System.out.println("C");
}

Answer: B then C. “A” is skipped because the error happens on the first line of the try.

Fibonacci — Naive Recursion
\[F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2), \quad F(0)=0,\ F(1)=1\]
def fib(n):
    if n &lt;= 1:
        return n
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2)
Simple and correct. But let’s trace fib(6):




fib(6) call tree





Time complexity: O(2ⁿ) — doubles with every step. Terrible!

LCS — Code
def lcs(s1, s2):
    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)
    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]

    for i in range(1, m + 1):
        for j in range(1, n + 1):
            if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1      # characters match!
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])  # take the best

    return dp[m][n]

print(lcs("ABCBDAB", "BDCABA"))  # → 4
print(lcs("AGGTAB",  "GXTXAYB")) # → 4
Time: O(m × n)
Space: O(m × n) (reducible to O(min(m,n)) with a rolling array)

The Code
def unique_paths(m, n):
    dp = [[1] * n for _ in range(m)]   # fill with 1s (base cases handled)

    for i in range(1, m):
        for j in range(1, n):
            dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]

    return dp[m-1][n-1]

print(unique_paths(3, 7))   # → 28
print(unique_paths(3, 2))   # → 3
print(unique_paths(1, 1))   # → 1
Time: O(m × n) — Space: O(m × n)

Space can be reduced to O(n) with a rolling array — we only ever look at the current and previous row.
def unique_paths_opt(m, n):
    row = [1] * n
    for _ in range(1, m):
        for j in range(1, n):
            row[j] += row[j-1]    # row[j] = old row[j] + new row[j-1]
    return row[-1]

Adjusting the Recurrence
Only change: if a cell has an obstacle, it contributes 0 paths.
def unique_paths_obstacles(grid):
    m, n = len(grid), len(grid[0])
    if grid[0][0] == 1 or grid[m-1][n-1] == 1:
        return 0    # start or end is blocked

    dp = [[0] * n for _ in range(m)]
    dp[0][0] = 1

    # First column: if any obstacle, all cells below it are blocked
    for i in range(1, m):
        dp[i][0] = dp[i-1][0] if grid[i][0] == 0 else 0

    # First row: same logic
    for j in range(1, n):
        dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-1] if grid[0][j] == 0 else 0

    # Fill the rest
    for i in range(1, m):
        for j in range(1, n):
            if grid[i][j] == 1:
                dp[i][j] = 0         # obstacle: no paths through here
            else:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]

    return dp[m-1][n-1]
